[{"id":"VH944752","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a graph with two curves plotted on it. The horizontal axis is labeled Reaction Progress and the vertical axis is labeled Potential Energy. The first curve, labeled X, starts about a quarter of the way up and to the right of the vertical axis, and moves briefly to the right horizontally.  It then moves up and to the right and peaks near the top of the vertical axis and at the middle of the horizontal axis.  It moves down and to the right until it reaches a point close to the horizontal axis on the right side near the end, where it continues to move horizontally to the right.  The curve, labeled Y, starts and ends at the same point as curve X does, and its horizontal segments overlap with those of curve X; however curve Y has 4 peaks that reach between one third to two thirds up the vertical axis.  The middle two peaks are higher than the outer peaks. \" height=\"171\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH944752.g02.png\" width=\"200\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">The diagram above shows the reaction energy profiles for a reaction with and without a catalyst. Which of the following identifies the reaction energy profile for the catalyzed reaction, and why?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH944752_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Profile <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X \"><math alttext=\"X \" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>X</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because a catalyst minimizes the number of elementary steps required for a reaction to proceed.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Profile <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"X \"><math alttext=\"X \" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>X</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because the activation energy for the reverse reaction is greater than for the forward reaction, which increases its rate.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Profile <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y \"><math alttext=\"Y \" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>Y</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because an increase in the number of transition states increases the rate of the reaction.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Profile <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"Y \"><math alttext=\"Y \" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>Y</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because it introduces a different reaction path that reduces the activation energy.</p>"],"answer":3}]